WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.336 --> 00:00:04.568
- An Air India Boeing 787 took off

00:00:04.568 --> 00:00:08.029
for what should have
been a routine nine-hour flight,

00:00:08.029 --> 00:00:10.044
but then ended up
crashing into buildings

00:00:10.044 --> 00:00:12.992
just half a minute after departure.

00:00:12.992 --> 00:00:14.425
(plane booms)

00:00:14.842 --> 00:00:15.774
Why?

00:00:15.774 --> 00:00:16.990
What actually happened?

00:00:18.223 --> 00:00:21.690
Well, I will get to the details
from the interim report soon,

00:00:21.690 --> 00:00:24.239
but first I want to talk
about the period leading up

00:00:24.239 --> 00:00:27.607
to its release
on the 11th of July, 2025.

00:00:28.506 --> 00:00:31.906
Unfortunately, in the immediate
aftermath of this tragedy,

00:00:31.906 --> 00:00:34.542
there were no real updates
from the investigators,

00:00:34.542 --> 00:00:36.658
which frankly isn't that surprising

00:00:36.658 --> 00:00:38.340
given how much they had to do

00:00:38.340 --> 00:00:39.890
and how careful they needed to be

00:00:39.890 --> 00:00:41.674
in weighing the information.

00:00:42.573 --> 00:00:43.757
But this also meant

00:00:43.757 --> 00:00:46.725
that there was
a substantial information vacuum,

00:00:46.725 --> 00:00:49.490
which gave rise to wild speculation

00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:51.373
or even worse, real trash

00:00:51.373 --> 00:00:53.810
in the form of deliberate misinformation

00:00:53.810 --> 00:00:55.926
that a very large section of the public

00:00:55.926 --> 00:00:58.591
just wasn't equipped to
distinguish from the truth.

00:00:59.109 --> 00:01:02.459
For example, several fake
interim reports were circulated

00:01:02.459 --> 00:01:04.842
and one of them claimed
that the captain's seat

00:01:04.842 --> 00:01:07.109
had slipped or fallen backwards,

00:01:07.109 --> 00:01:08.443
causing him to inadvertently

00:01:08.443 --> 00:01:11.559
pull back on the thrust
levers without even realizing it.

00:01:12.825 --> 00:01:15.725
Now that actually did happen
to an Air India Express flight,

00:01:15.725 --> 00:01:19.757
a Boeing 737-800, which
I covered in a different video.

00:01:19.757 --> 00:01:21.589
But that also meant
that these hoaxsters

00:01:21.589 --> 00:01:23.921
were now using a mix of AI tools

00:01:23.921 --> 00:01:26.856
and real stories to create narratives

00:01:26.856 --> 00:01:29.406
that initially
looked really believable,

00:01:29.406 --> 00:01:31.689
thanks to details
from that older story

00:01:31.689 --> 00:01:32.855
and its final report.

00:01:33.889 --> 00:01:35.722
Now I know that not everyone

00:01:35.722 --> 00:01:37.655
can quickly identify these scams.

00:01:38.173 --> 00:01:41.552
They are designed
to deceive and they really do.

00:01:41.552 --> 00:01:44.782
And in events like this,
it's always important

00:01:44.782 --> 00:01:48.464
to turn to reliable sources
and to think critically,

00:01:48.464 --> 00:01:50.948
especially when you see
something really shocking

00:01:50.948 --> 00:01:53.379
being sent to you
from a friend or colleague.

00:01:54.246 --> 00:01:57.163
Since at least some
of this fabricated material

00:01:57.163 --> 00:01:59.495
is based on real events and reports,

00:01:59.495 --> 00:02:01.347
it looks super convincing,

00:02:01.347 --> 00:02:06.446
even to industry insiders
and that just makes my blood boil.

00:02:07.229 --> 00:02:10.681
Not only do we have
a horrible tragedy on our hands,

00:02:10.681 --> 00:02:13.412
the first fatal crash of a Boeing 787

00:02:13.412 --> 00:02:15.696
and the deadliest crash in a decade,

00:02:15.696 --> 00:02:17.495
no, we also have people

00:02:17.495 --> 00:02:20.597
knowingly spreading AI-generated nonsense

00:02:20.597 --> 00:02:22.480
just to get some temporary attention

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:25.030
or for some other nefarious motives.

00:02:25.979 --> 00:02:29.032
That is actually a big
part of why my team and I

00:02:29.032 --> 00:02:30.962
have been following this story closely

00:02:30.962 --> 00:02:34.274
and making frequent video
updates for you guys,

00:02:34.274 --> 00:02:36.274
and I hope you appreciate that.

00:02:37.273 --> 00:02:40.490
But now, finally, we
have a preliminary report,

00:02:40.490 --> 00:02:43.907
and while it still doesn't include
any definitive conclusions,

00:02:43.907 --> 00:02:46.724
it sheds a lot of light
on what happened.

00:02:47.173 --> 00:02:50.890
So this video is
all about the facts here,

00:02:50.890 --> 00:02:53.257
what we do know and what it means,

00:02:53.257 --> 00:02:54.641
and also what we don't know,

00:02:54.641 --> 00:02:56.441
which is just as important.

00:02:56.873 --> 00:02:59.143
And it's also about
what you can do from now on

00:02:59.143 --> 00:03:00.825
to remain well informed.

00:03:01.974 --> 00:03:05.789
This tragedy happened
on Thursday the 12th of June, 2025,

00:03:05.789 --> 00:03:08.090
involving Air India Flight 171

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:11.406
from Ahmedabad to London's
Gatwick Airport in the UK.

00:03:12.523 --> 00:03:15.940
Until this tragic event,
Flight 171 was a daily service

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:18.342
for Air India, departing
early in the afternoon.

00:03:18.342 --> 00:03:20.476
And on this day,
the aircraft had been scheduled

00:03:20.476 --> 00:03:22.941
to depart at 1310 local time.

00:03:23.939 --> 00:03:26.490
The flight's captain
was a 56-year-old male

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:30.740
who had a total flight
experience of 15,638 hours,

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:34.207
and nearly 8,600 hours
was on the Boeing 787,

00:03:34.207 --> 00:03:37.842
of which 8,260
was as pilot-in-command.

00:03:38.924 --> 00:03:41.557
Now, earlier local news reports said

00:03:41.557 --> 00:03:43.557
that he was also
a line-training captain

00:03:43.557 --> 00:03:45.907
with Air India and that he
planned to retire soon,

00:03:45.907 --> 00:03:48.557
but that was not
mentioned in the report.

00:03:49.640 --> 00:03:51.707
His first officer was 32 years old

00:03:51.707 --> 00:03:55.807
and had a total flight
experience of 3,403 hours,

00:03:55.807 --> 00:03:59.857
of which 1,128 hours were
flown on the Boeing 787.

00:04:00.490 --> 00:04:04.007
And it's important to
note here that for this flight,

00:04:04.007 --> 00:04:05.840
the first officer was pilot flying

00:04:05.840 --> 00:04:07.823
and the captain was pilot monitoring.

00:04:09.342 --> 00:04:11.376
As part of their pre-flight preparation,

00:04:11.376 --> 00:04:13.804
the two pilots underwent
some medical checks,

00:04:13.804 --> 00:04:15.539
including a breath analyzer test,

00:04:15.539 --> 00:04:17.123
which showed that they were both fit

00:04:17.123 --> 00:04:18.940
to operate the flight over to Gatwick.

00:04:19.838 --> 00:04:22.722
Both pilots also seemed
to have gotten adequate rest

00:04:22.722 --> 00:04:25.072
before the flight,
according to the report.

00:04:26.253 --> 00:04:27.786
One of the speculations we heard

00:04:27.786 --> 00:04:30.853
before the preliminary
report was released

00:04:30.853 --> 00:04:33.886
was that the aircraft might
have been carrying something

00:04:33.886 --> 00:04:36.152
that could have affected
the instruments on board,

00:04:36.552 --> 00:04:38.611
but the load manifest showed

00:04:38.611 --> 00:04:41.571
that there were no dangerous
goods on board this flight.

00:04:43.071 --> 00:04:45.155
Anyway, the pilots' fuel calculations,

00:04:45.155 --> 00:04:48.271
the rest of the loadsheet
as well as the V-speed calculations

00:04:48.271 --> 00:04:51.221
didn't raise any flags
for the investigations either.

00:04:51.554 --> 00:04:54.270
Everything was apparently
within allowable limits.

00:04:55.588 --> 00:04:56.706
Once the crew were ready,

00:04:56.706 --> 00:04:58.104
they taxied out for departure

00:04:58.104 --> 00:05:00.238
about half an hour behind schedule

00:05:00.238 --> 00:05:02.103
towards Runway 23.

00:05:02.571 --> 00:05:05.255
Now, Ahmedabad only has one runway,

00:05:05.255 --> 00:05:07.271
and its parallel taxiway doesn't run

00:05:07.271 --> 00:05:09.837
all the way to the
threshold for Runway 23.

00:05:10.271 --> 00:05:12.472
And this meant that the
crew had to taxi out

00:05:12.472 --> 00:05:15.488
and enter the runway
from taxiway Romeo four,

00:05:15.488 --> 00:05:20.006
which is connecting close
to about halfway down the runway.

00:05:20.971 --> 00:05:24.188
Now, initial ADS-B data
of the plane's taxi route

00:05:24.188 --> 00:05:26.070
was missing quite a lot of data points,

00:05:26.070 --> 00:05:28.573
which also created
some initial controversy,

00:05:28.988 --> 00:05:31.289
where some suspected that the crew

00:05:31.289 --> 00:05:32.855
might have tried to take off from

00:05:32.855 --> 00:05:36.222
that intersection taxiway, Romeo Four

00:05:36.222 --> 00:05:37.888
but later reporting,

00:05:37.888 --> 00:05:40.673
and, of course,
this preliminary report confirmed

00:05:40.673 --> 00:05:42.838
that the 787 did not take off

00:05:42.838 --> 00:05:44.521
from that midfield position.

00:05:44.936 --> 00:05:46.905
Instead, the flight crew backtracked

00:05:46.905 --> 00:05:49.735
to the threshold of the 3,505-meter,

00:05:49.735 --> 00:05:52.569
or 11,500 feet long runway,

00:05:52.569 --> 00:05:55.318
and then made a full length takeoff.

00:05:56.001 --> 00:05:59.383
Now Ahmedabad Airport is only 58 meters

00:05:59.383 --> 00:06:01.767
or 189 feet above sea level,

00:06:01.767 --> 00:06:03.668
but at the time of their departure,

00:06:03.668 --> 00:06:06.585
the high temperature
of around 37 degrees Celsius,

00:06:06.585 --> 00:06:10.617
or 98.6 Fahrenheit,
meant that the density altitude

00:06:10.617 --> 00:06:12.769
was around 3,200 feet.

00:06:13.102 --> 00:06:15.568
This requires a bit extra
performance from the aircraft,

00:06:15.568 --> 00:06:17.451
but nothing that the Boeing 787

00:06:17.451 --> 00:06:21.335
and its mighty GEnx engines
couldn't handle on this day.

00:06:21.335 --> 00:06:23.019
And, of course, these are conditions

00:06:23.019 --> 00:06:25.037
that crews flying in and out of India

00:06:25.037 --> 00:06:27.236
would have been entirely familiar with.

00:06:28.351 --> 00:06:29.952
The crew started their takeoff roll

00:06:29.952 --> 00:06:33.602
at time 0807 and 37 seconds UTC,

00:06:33.602 --> 00:06:36.387
and then reached
their V1 decision speed

00:06:36.387 --> 00:06:37.784
just under a minute later,

00:06:37.784 --> 00:06:40.034
which would be
considered completely normal

00:06:40.034 --> 00:06:41.518
for their takeoff weight.

00:06:42.319 --> 00:06:44.914
The plane's weight on
wheel switches then indicated

00:06:44.914 --> 00:06:49.164
that they lifted off at time
0808 and 39 seconds.

00:06:49.164 --> 00:06:52.094
And initially, all videos
taken from this event showed

00:06:52.094 --> 00:06:54.913
that they achieved
a normal positive rate of climb.

00:06:55.865 --> 00:06:59.066
But very soon, these
same videos then showed

00:06:59.066 --> 00:07:00.615
that this climb flattened out

00:07:00.615 --> 00:07:03.113
and then quickly turned into a descent,

00:07:03.113 --> 00:07:05.695
one that the aircraft
then never recovered from.

